context: The gates of the Temple of Jerusalem used <a0_0><b5_0>Corinthian bronze<b5_0/><a0_0/> made by <a1_0><b6_0>depletion gilding<b6_0/><a1_0/>. It was most prevalent in <a2_0><b7_0>Alexandria<b7_0/><a2_0/>, where alchemy is thought to have begun. In ancient India, <a3_0><b8_0>copper<b8_0/><a3_0/> was used in the holistic medical science Ayurveda for surgical instruments and other medical equipment. Ancient Egyptians (~2400 BC) used copper for sterilizing wounds and drinking water, and later on for headaches, burns, and itching. The <a4_0><b9_0>Baghdad Battery<b9_0/><a4_0/>, with copper cylinders soldered to lead, dates back to 248 BC to AD 226 and resembles a galvanic cell, leading people to believe this was the first battery; the claim has not been verified.
